You could use [`flatMap`][1] over the [entries][2] of the object

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    const products = {
      bread: 1,
      milk: 2,
      cheese: 2,
      chicken: 1,
    }

    const output = Object.entries(products).flatMap(([k, v]) =&gt; Array(v).fill(k))

    console.log(output)

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;


  [1]: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Array/flatMap
  [2]: https://developer.mozilla.org/en/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Object/entries

With lodash you can iterate the array with `_.flatMap()`. Create the the callback using `_.overArgs()` that will pass the value (via `_.identity()`) and the key (wrapped with `_.constant()`) to `_.times()`:

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    const obj = {
      products: {
        bread: 1,
        milk: 2,
        cheese: 2,
        chicken: 1,
      }
    }

    const result = _.flatMap(obj.products, _.overArgs(_.times, [_.identity, _.constant]))
      
    console.log(result)

&lt;!-- language: lang-html --&gt;

    &lt;script src=&quot;https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/lodash.js/4.17.15/lodash.js&quot;&gt;&lt;/script&gt;

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

